This paper is likely to belong to the sub-category of cs.LG (Machine Learning) as it focuses on regularization techniques for deep neural networks to improve generalization and adversarial robustness. It also involves empirical evaluations of the regularized models. 

It is also likely to belong to cs.CV (Computer Vision) as the paper discusses the use of gradient norms of images for attack detection. 

Additionally, it could belong to cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) as deep neural networks are a popular tool in AI research. 

The paper also discusses adversarial attacks, which could place it in the sub-category of cs.CR (Cryptography and Security). 

Finally, the use of Lipschitz regularization could place it in the sub-category of cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing).
